Thoughts of a profound and astute nature come to some far easier than others. One particular activity that seems to conquer many creative thoughts within myself is the appreciation and observation various types of art. By staring at many paintings, illustrations and sculptures in the same fashion our ancestor's did, I find a flow of thought that might not have otherwise occurred. In fact, I sometimes find the inspiration induced by partaking in such stimulus can often create far too high a volume of thought for one to even keep up with. In the same way, I find observing society as if one is somehow removed, is the same as the observation of a grand, troublesome, forever changing painting that screams at us to make sense of its abnormality. There are many creative minds who simply haven't taken the time to adapt their wasted skills, or to even admit their own capabilities of doing so. The development of such skills begin when one directs the majority of one's cognitive effort that is usually saved for the workplace or one's favourite hobby, to the simple process of thought itself. I could give a million examples as to how the development of one's inner creativity works, but that's just how it applies to me. Those who willingly or unwillingly misunderstand what I'm saying, fear not, you're doing exactly as I'd expect of you already. However, If my words resonate with you, then your mind suggests that you're either one of the few, or, one of the few who've yet to join us.

When I was young I felt comfort within the simple design of my grandparents homes. Today, instead of such homely comfort, we're surrounded by the hellish nature of modernistic decors. You may have once been bored, or unimpressed, by the simplistic nature of old fashioned homes. But, the truth is, you was truly at home. We've been led to believe that we're past such out-dated design, when in reality, our subconscious yearns for it's return. Those of you with relatives who are old enough to possess such homes will know of rooms without a scrap of technology. Gifted instead, with a smell and a feel of a wholesome, culturally significant dwelling. That smell, like the feeling that comes with it, will soon disappear altogether, alongside the designs we've selfishly left behind. The next time you're in a hurry to leave, or ready to dismiss the interior designs of our recent ancestors, remember that any day now, we shall see, smell, feel, love, and know their like no more.

The tale of #Medusa is in fact one of great tragedy. Medusa had been admired for her beauty within Athens, Greece. A person who was kind and obeyed the Greek gods of the time. Her love for 'Athena Goddess of War' led her to becoming the priestess of Athena‚Äôs temple, a role unimaginable by the standards of mono-theism. Men from far and wide would travel to gaze upon her beauty until she became a symbol of beauty itself. Medusa's beauty became so renowned it made Athena herself jealous. Poseidon 'God of the Sea' had been seeking Medusa's affection, but faced rejection due to her wanting to remain pure. Poseidon, eventually took Medusa by force, whilst Athena did nothing to protect her. Poseidon would rape Medusa and then leaver her stranded with her image in utter ruin. As Medusa was no longer pure, Athena used the excuse to curse Medusa for the sins she could have prevented. Medusa‚Äôs once beautiful hair, was turned into a head of venomous snakes. And to ensure no man may look upon her again, Medusa‚Äôs eyes, would turn those who looked at them to stone. Medusa couldn‚Äôt even look into anyone‚Äôs eyes, never mind seek some kind of comfort. Medusa was also unable to turn herself into stone, and so the men who once admired her, strove to end her life for glory. Medusa was forced to hide and fight off her attackers until Zeus 'King of Gods' ordered his son Perseus to behead what was now considered a monster. The injustice of this story is a great lesson of hardship and misfortune from the ancient world. Unlike many other stories or religious scripture, many tales of the 'Old Gods' are but ways to explain our fear and pain as opposed to a story with a just ending. For years the tale of Medusa seems to be told as a form of heroism as opposed to tragedy, but for those who know the full detail of this story, it's a touching tragedy of a woman, as opposed to the heroic victory of a man.

The Bottle Inn is a 16th-century public house at Marshwood in Dorset, which hosted the World Nettle Eating Championship. It is a Grade II Listed Building. The building started life in 1585, as an ale house, being close to a church where people came to pay their tithes. It was named The Bottle Inn, some time late in the 18th century, when it became the first inn in the area to sell bottled beers. The Bottle Inn was purchased as a free house (not tied to any one brewery) in 1982 from Ushers Brewery by Michael and Pauline Brookes. In 2014, the public house won the CAMRA award for West Dorset pub of the year. The Bottle Inn hosted the annual World Nettle Eating Championships as part of a charity beer festival. Competitors are served 2-foot (0.61 m) long stalks of stinging nettles from which they pluck and eat the leaves. After an hour the bare stalks are measured and the winner is the competitor with the greatest accumulated length of nettles. The contest began in the late 1980's when two farmers argued over who had the longest stinging nettles in their field and evolved into the World Nettle Eating Championships when one of the farmers promised to eat any nettle which was longer than his. The championship has separate men‚Äôs and women‚Äôs sections and attracts competitors from as far afield as Canada and Australia. In June 2010 Sam Cunningham, a fishmonger from Somerset won the contest, after eating 74 feet (23 m) of nettles. In June 2014 Phillip Thorne, a chef from Colyton, Devon won the contest, after eating 80 feet (24 m) of nettles. In 2017 the Overall Champion was Jonathan Searle from Solihull who munched his way through 70 feet of nettles whilst the Women's Prize went to Kate Ribton of Stoke St Gregory, in Somerset, who got through 28 feet (8.5 m) of the plant. On this day: In 871, West Saxon forces led by King √Üthelred and his brother Alfred (King Alfred the great) successfully defeated the invading Viking forces led by Bagsecg and Haldan at the battle of Ashdown. The battle was fierce, and the west saxon army suffered heavy losses against the imposing Vikings. However, √Üthelred, under major risk of being flanked by overwhelming Viking forces, decided to carry out a preemptive attack and led his men in a charge up hill. Soon battle eschewed and raged around a small thorn tree and, finally, the west saxons were victorious. Yet, Ashdown was a short-lived victory, as it was followed by two defeats, one at Basing and the other at Meretun. Luck worsened, as soon after Easter, which fell on 15 April that year, √Üthelred died and was succeeded by his brother Alfred. Finally, although the location of Ashdown is not known, the battle is usually thought to have occurred at Kingstanding Hill, South Oxfordshire: a claim that is frequently disputed by other historians.

On this day: In 1720, Charles Edward Stuart (popularly known as Bonnie Prince Charles) was born in Rome to the exiled stuart court. As the grandson of the deposed King James II, Charles was thought by many - especially Catholics, Scotsmen, and Irishmen - to be the true and legitimate claiment to the British throne. After being raised and educated in Italy, Charles, in 1744, travelled to France to take part in a planned invasion to restore the Stuart Monarchy under his father (James Francis Edward Stuart). When the French invasion fleet was partly wrecked by storms, Charles resolved to proceed to scotland after discussion with leading Jacobites. These talks resulted in Charles landing by ship on the west coast of Scotland, leading to the events that would start the Jacobite rising of 1745. Contrary to popular opinion, the early stages of the rising were all but in the favour of the Jacobites; with Charles' forces winning the crucial battles of Prestonpans (September 1745) and Falkirk Muir (January 1745). However, by April 1746, Charles' forces were defeated at the battle of Culloden, which effectively ended the Jacobite cause. While there were subsequent attempts, such as the planned French invasion in 1759, Charles was unable to restore the Stuart dynasty. With the Jacobite Cause lost, Charles continued his life in exile, living in France and later in Italy. He died in Roman,1788 (aged 67)

url_description: Phoenix Music International is pleased to present the official music video for 'Eternal Love' by PJ & Duncan, otherwise known as Ant & Dec. 'Eternal Love' features on PJ & Duncan's 1994 album, 'Psyche', which also features the No. 1 hit song, 'Let's Get Ready to Rhumble'. 'Let's Get Ready to Rhumble' was released in the United Kingdom on 11 July 1994 as the third single from PJ & Duncan's debut studio album 'Psyche'.The single was re-released in March 2013 . The song peaked at number one on the UK Singles Chart in its first week of new release, becoming their first ever single to reach that spot. The song was also performed on Ant & Dec's Saturday Night Takeaway. The pub gave birth to a song made famous during a Victorian era of theatrical entertainment named 'Music Hall'. The song "Down at the old Bull and Bush"which dates somewhere in the early 1910‚Äôs was sung by Florrie Forde and can still be found online or even purchased on vinyl today. "Come, come, come and make eyes at me Down at the Old Bull and Bush, Come, come, drink some port wine with me, Down at the Old Bull and Bush, Hear the little German Band, Just let me hold your hand dear, Do, do come and have a drink or two Down at the Old Bull and Bush, Bush, Bush Come, come, come and make eyes at me" I can tell you form listening to the song, its a charm and the thought of anything happening to this pub with such a memory attached it makes me shudder.

Pubs Of The Industrial Revolution Part 2 #Ironbridge, #Shropshire Return To The Boat Inn, #Jackfield, #Telford. üéô @VinnieSull1van We return to the amazing and welcoming 'Boat Inn' where we was once more received with open arms but it's friendly landlord. it touched us when he told us that after our video which included Morris Dancers, three more groups of Morris Dancers and even Belly handers had visited the pub off the back of our video. This pub has flood many times due it it sitting directly beside the river Severn at the bottom of a beautiful valley. The garden, the brickwork and the interior are truly culturally charming as well as welcoming and homely. Thank you once again for yet another charming tour and a chance to reflect upon on of our early episodes. The views and the memories combined are why this public house will always be special to me on a personal level. -- The iconic region of Ironbridge contains a huge array of important history which effected not only Britain, but the entire world. The pubs of Ironbridge served the early workers of the industrial revolution who were busy creating the world in which we know today. Strangely the modern media creates a fictional reality for the building of western architecture and industry, wrongly neglecting the real, hard working people of the factories who built Britain and beyond. The True Story of the Cragg Vale Coiners. Up in Yorkshire in the 1760s, the industrial revolution was steaming ahead at full pelt. The rich were getting richer, through the building of cotton mills and factories, while the poor grew poorer. Suffering ensued. There was great poverty, especially in the area of Cragg Vale, near Hebden Bridge, which was populated by weavers, land-workers and their families. A man named David Hartley ‚Äì known as ‚ÄúKing David‚Äù, and played by Socha ‚Äì came up with a Robin-Hood-esque idea: he would lead a gang of people who would counterfeit coins to bring money back to their community. His idea was to get coins locally from crooked officials, shop owners or publicans, then smelt the original metals with base ores. This could be done by what was known as ‚Äòclipping‚Äô: shaving the edges off coins and milling them, meaning the original coins were imperceptibly smaller, while the offcuts could then be used to make new counterfeit coins, some of which were European, that then had the official designs stamped onto them. These coins were then placed back into circulation, and, according to the Yorkshire Examiner: ‚ÄúBy the end of the 1760s, approximately ¬£3.5m (¬£515m in today's money) of Coiner-forged coins had been paid into the Bank of England. The effect on the British economy was disastrous, devaluing the Pound by 9 percent.‚Äù The scheme continued successfully for almost 10 years, as the moors and vales of Cragg Vale were a relatively isolated place compared to the bigger cities in England. Clipping was a treasonous offence punishable by death and by 1769, rumours began circulating in parliament about a group committing fraud in Yorkshire. A public official, William Dighton, was put on to the gang of coiners, which now numbered about 80 people. One of the counterfeit coiners, James Broadbent, betrayed the group and gave evidence that revealed the conspirators in exchange for leniency of his own crimes. Dighton then arrested Hartley, which enraged his brother, Isaac. He rallied a gang of men who conspired to kill Broadbent (and in probably one of the earliest forms of crowdsourcing, raised 100 guineas from people who supported the plan) and on 10 November, 1769, two farm workers, Matthew Normanton and Robert Thomas, fatally shot Broadbent. The punishment The Marquess of Rockingham (and also former Prime Minister) Charles Watson-Wentworth was charged with finding the murderers, and by Christmas day of that same year, he had arrested 30 coiners. This is where The Gallows Pole name comes in: David Hartley was hanged at York Tyburn on April 28, 1770. Broadbent‚Äôs murderers were both hanged as well: Thomas on August 6, 1774 and Normanton on April 15, 1775. Hartley‚Äôs brother, Isaac, managed to escape, and lived until 1815.

One witness gave Collins a good character. COLLINS - GUILTY - DEATH . Aged 16. QUIN - NOT GUILTY .[Friday, May 28.]

"Shall I sell it;" Quin said, "What do you want for it?" he said, "Oh, I shan't sell it now;" in about five minutes another girl came in - the officer came in, and took Collins and the hat; Quin was taken next day. Collins. Q. Did I offer the hat for sale? A. You did. THOMAS SMITH . I am a Police-constable. In consequence of information from a private watchman, I went to the Robart's Arms, about a quarter to eleven o'clock- I had not seen the prisoners; I found them at the Robart's Arms, with two females - I inquired of Collins if he had a hat to sell - he took it up; it was on his left-hand side, on the settle - he said, "Is this it?" I asked what he meant by saying that - one of the females rose up, and said, "Oh, he knows nothing at all about it;" I had said nothing about any robbery or any thing; I told her to mind her own business; she sat down, and the colour came in Quin's face very much - I went to the landlady, made inquiry, and then took Collins with the hat; I found some receipts in it - Collins had a jacket on: I did not search him. WILLIAM MITCHELL . I am a Police-constable. I apprehended Quin on the 18th, in Stepney-fields, and asked where he was the night before; he said at the Robart's Arms - I asked at what time he was there; he said he did not know exactly - I asked how long he was there before Collins came in; he said about an hour - I asked if he had seen Collins before he came in there; he said he had been with him to Ratcliff-highway, and that he knew nothing of the robbery. RICHARD LAWLEY. This is the hat I had on; this 2d. and 3d. stamps were in it - they are not receipts; I called Watch! Watch! immediately I came to myself. Quin's Defence. When he asked if I had a hat for sale, I said No - there was one he said he had picked up coming over the fields; one of the girls said it would do for his mother or father. Collins' Defence. I did not offer it for sale. SARAH FORD . I was with Collins - he came along by the turning of the Robart's Arms, a little after ten o'clock, and this hat lay on the dung-heap; he said to me, "What is it?" I said I believed it was a dog - he went and took it up, and said, "It is a hat, shall I take it with me?" I said, "Yes, if you don't, somebody else will," and he took it - the dung-heap is in the turning in Vinegar-lane; he went strait along into the Robert's Arms with it; I went with him, and was there when the Police-man took him out - I had been no where; we came from Bluegatefields - I know Quin; the next witness keeps company with him - I live with my mother, who does needlework for a shop in Smithfield; I get my bread by needlework- I had finished my work, and came out for a walk; Collins asked me to walk with him - I left home about ten o'clock, and went into the public-house between ten and eleven, it was nearer eleven; I have known him for years- I was standing at my door, and he asked me to go to the Robart's Arms with him; they say the prosecutor was knocked down at this turning, but we do not know it - I did not cry "Halves" when the hat was found. MARY COLLINS . I am the prisoner's sister. I was at the public-house with the prisoner Quin, at the time the hat was brought in. Q. How came you there? A. We were going along, and he asked me to go in and have a pint of beer with him- I knew Ford before, and had seen him that evening at six o'clock, in the highway, between Old and New Gravel-lane; we did not agree to meet at the public-house - I do not know how we met, but suppose they were going along, and he saw this hat, and picked it up; I did not see it till Collins brought it in - I get my bread by needlework, and live with my mother; I had just left off work, was going home, and met Quin - we were in the public-house about half an hour before the hat was brought in; I had been with Quin from eight to ten o'clock. Q. How came you to say you had just left off work? A. I left off work at eight o'clock, and Quin and I had been standing talking together in the highway, down by where I live.

Who was Gottfried Wilhelm Von Leibniz? Gottfried Wilhelm Von Leibniz (1646-1716) was a 17th century German polymath genius. A Mathematician, Philosopher, Physicist, Engineer, Inventor, Polyglot, diplomat, librarian and amongst other things an outstanding mind. Although his contributions to knowledge are far too numerous to name, he is best remembered for five great feats of genius: The discover of Calculus alongside Isaac Newton, the inventor of the first fully functional mechanical calculator, one of the main exponents of continental rationalism, the co-inventor with papin of the steam engine and the discoverer of binary code (the language of computers). However, due to disputes with Newton concerning his discovery of calculus, Leibniz was subject to much unfair accusation and abuse. As such, he published very little of his brilliance and preferred to write letters to the leading intellectual figures of his day, alongside private manuscripts. His total works have yet to be fully categorised, translated and published. Due to these lifelong inconveniences, Leibniz lived the life of a diplomat and at times that of a librarian and Engineer. Although, he always remained a lifelong optimist; an optimist that believed in the ability of reason to help humanity thrive and grow. His greatest ambition, and for sure a result of his extreme optimism, was to construct what he called an ‚ÄúAlgebra of thought‚Äù whereby all theoretical disputes could be solved computationally, given that the metaphysical code was right of course. Yet, despite this great dream never being completely fulfilled; Leibniz like always stayed optimistic for the future. Believing that: ‚ÄúThis language will be the greatest instrument of reason,‚Äù for ‚Äúwhen there are disputes among persons, we can simply say: Let us calculate, without further ado, and see who is right‚Äù. I hope too that he was right, yet only time will tell. Yet alongside these contributions, the blueprinting of energy efficient windmills, water pumps, mine shafts, even a submarine! Like many a great genius Leibniz, rather tragically, never got near the reception and admiration that he so rightfully deserved and at the age of 70 died poor and abandoned in his Hanover apartment. With his remains treated akin to that of a pauper, unmarked and uncharted for. Due to the harsh satirisation by Voltaire in Candide, few payed Leibniz the time of day. One can only speculate as to how advanced society would have been if his genius was truly given the time of day that it so rightfully deserved. Even now, scholars discover and analyse his magnificent writings with astonishment and excitement. This brief description only touches the iceberg of this profound thinker. The following posts will hopefully do more justice to such a great man. Yet I‚Äôll leave you with this quote from Diderot: ‚ÄúWhen you return to yourself and compare the talents you received with those of Leibniz, you‚Äôre tempted to throw the books away and quietly die into some hidden corner of the world.‚Äù

The distinctions of knowledges: the fallacy of logical Mysticism In concerning the distinction and differentiation of different knowledges, we must by reason categorise the organisations in which the mind orders rational and empirical thought. As is mostly commonly agreed upon in epistemology, the synthetic-analytic distinction as developed by Kant shall be used to analytically order the categories of knowledge. Analytic a priori statements: this form of knowledge refers to statements that prove themselves without the need of external evidence. As such, this division is reverent to knowledges that is completely logical and tautological: Logic, Mathematics and self referential statements I.e ‚Äúall bachelors are unmarried men‚Äù are sound exemplars. Hence, this knowledge requires only pure reason to express its self, even if the semantic knowledge requires external experience. Yet this knowledge is restricted in its heuristic ability to verify empirical data. Synthetic a posterior statements: this form of knowledge refers to statements that form a resolute relation between two or more distinct and external factors I.e ‚ÄúIt is raining outside‚Äù, nothing about ‚Äòoutside‚Äô predicates raining, hence requiring a posterior sense date to conceive logically via empirical inference. This form of knowledge constitutes any descriptive statements, and is the meta-logical basis for the sciences and inductive/statistical references. Its restriction lies with the problem of induction as stated by Hume. Analytic a posteriori statements: knowledge of this kind is logically impossible to express via reason and by extension, language its self. As no piece of logical or empirical reference can substantiate the claim that there are tautologous statements that describe the external world before experienced via sense perception. The Boy On The Moor by Annette Von Droste Hulshoff 'Tis an eerie thing o'er the moor to fare When the eddies of peat-smoke justle, When the wraiths of mist whirl here and there And wind-blown tendrils tussle, When every step starts a hidden spring And the trodden moss-tufts hiss and sing 'Tis an eerie thing o'er the moor to fare When the tangled reed-beds rustle. The child with his primer sets out alone And speeds as if he were hunted, The wind goes by with a hollow moan-- There's a noise in the hedge-row stunted. 'Tis the turf-digger's ghost, near-by he dwells, And for drink his master's turf he sells. "Whoo! whoo!" comes a sound like a stray cow's groan; The poor boy's courage is daunted. Then stumps loom up beside the ditch, Uncannily nod the bushes, The boy running on, each nerve a twitch, Through a jungle of spear-grass pushes. And where it trickles and crackles apace Is the Spinner's unholy hiding-place, The home of the curs√®d Spinning-witch Who turns her wheel 'mid the rushes. On, ever on, goes the fearsome rout, In pursuit through that region fenny, At each wild stride the bubbles burst out, And the sounds from beneath are many. Until at length from the midst of the din Comes the squeak of a spectral violin, That must be the rascally fiddler lout Who ran off with the bridal penny! The turf splits open, and from the hole Bursts forth an unhappy sighing, "Alas, alas, for my wretched soul!" 'Tis poor damned Margaret crying! The lad he leaps like a wounded deer, And were not his guardian angel near Some digger might find in a marshy knoll Where his little bleached bones were lying. But the ground grows firmer beneath his feet, And there from over the meadow A lamp is flickering homely-sweet; The boy at the edge of the shadow Looks back as he pauses to take his breath, And in his glance is the fear of death. 'Twas eerie there 'mid the sedge and peat, Ah, that was a place to dread, O!

David Hume: A Treatise of Human Nature Book 1: Of the understanding Part 1: of ideas, their origin, composition, connection, abstraction and etc. Section 1: Of the origin of our ideas >> Hume conceives reality based of our impressions and ideas. >> Impressions are the perceptive inferences made by our senses of the reality surrounding us >> Ideas are the concepts we form based of our immediate impressions e.g Redness from a red apple. They cannot be separated from our impressions. >> He further divides the distinction into simple and complex >>Simple impressions always correspond and equivocate and predate our simple ideas. E.g Our idea of red is equal to our impression and is only formed by our impression. Even when non-perceptive e.g in darkness, our ideas still reflect our impressions and can only be made by constituting impressions. Yet are ideas are not immutable as our impressions always change based of changing perceptions. >> Hence Hume‚Äôs first maxim of Human Nature: ‚ÄúThat all our simple ideas in their first appearance are derived from simple impressions, which are correspondent to them, and which they exactly represent‚Äù. >> Complex ideas are the summation of simple ideas: however they do not always relate to our complex impressions e.g New Jerusalem having a pavement of Gold with walls of rubies. >> #davidhumeweek

A subject that has always remained dear and close, one to which I am most proficient and well versed in, yet rarely discuss in conversation: I am of course referring to mathematics, especially to its most sublime form, pure mathematics. To me and as to other great mathematicians, the subject is but the definition of pure reason, an abstract study that attempts to describe the facets of reality either by conceptualising abstract quantities from empirical finding (Applied) or from rationalised axioms (Pure). As such, mathematics is more then mere counting, and consists of four main topic areas and one Meta-Mathematical area. These being as follows: numbers (arithmetic and number theory), formulas and related structure (geometry and or topology), and quantities and their changes ( Calculus and analysis). With meta-mathematics consisting of Logic and set theory that attempt to solve, prove and deduce the axiomatic and theoretical proofs of mathematics as whole. As such, the mathematician uses a variety of methods to prove, categorise and periodically stage the steps of the branches. With mathematical proofs serving as the Pure staging of deductive rules from previous axioms, formulas or sequences to further construct wider rules of concerning abstract concepts: example being Euler‚Äôs Identity. While mathematical models serve as the applied staging of theories constructed around empirically backed data used most often in: physics, statistics,economics, finance,psychology and etc. Example: The motion equations that describe the prescribed movement and temporal displacement and distances of a moved object in a plane. The upcoming parts will continue to explain in thorough detail the structure, problems and questions all relating to this great and bountiful subject #Thequestionofmathematics Part.1

Episode 5: Snob Screens (Britain's lost & living pubs) We was lucky enough to pick the Lamb as our pub of choice when seeking a venue to show you what snob screens are. A wonderful and helpful ex-tour guide who works there gave us a walk through the pub and it's stunning features. This episode speaks of the class system of Victorian England and the methods used to keep the classes separated when in drinking venues. Snob screens can still be found in some British public houses since their use in the Victorian era. Usually installed in rows, they're made up of etched panes of glass in movable wooden frames. We had a wonderful day and deeply thank the staff at 'The Lamb' (Grade II listed pub at 94 Lamb's Conduit Street, Bloomsbury, London) and the kind reception we received. We cannot advise enough that you head down and enjoy this amazing location and take in it's inspiring history.

Art By Frank Skarbina, All Souls Day (Hedwig Cemetery) 1896 Recently I was in sight of a graveyard at night and noticed lanterns with candles burning beside the graves. It dawned on me just how much care others put into those graves, even during the night. It filled me with thought as to each of their stories and highlighted the lives they must have touched. It looked to me like each of the souls buried lived on in the dark, each flame represented a human who's time is supposed to have run out... Yet thanks to others live on long after death, so people like me, still can't help but notice them.

The Death of Socrates by Jacques-Louis David (1787) Socrates the Greek philosopher from Athens sits waiting and preparing to face his death as his wife cries beside him. The old man at the foot of the bed is Plato despite the fact he'd have been a young pupil of Socrates at the time. Socrates was know for saying ‚ÄúThe only true wisdom is in knowing that you know nothing‚Äù in the face of the theists of the day. Meletus accused Socrates of atheism. Socrates is then said to have noted the contradiction between atheism and worshipping false gods in an effort to seek sense from his accusers. He's then said to have claimed that he is "God's gift" to the Athenians seeking freedom of thought & discussion. The jurors of his trial favoured the death penalty, which he accepted & lived out as bravely as he could for his followers. Here they surround him through his final moment's, many still argue over his death & the justifications made at for it. He'd lead others to finally, think for themselves

Their battle cries, filled the skies Fighting for what they believed, For good, for hope, for life and for love. Oh how they were deceived. Now they rest beneath the soil, Despite all hope and prayer. Unknowing why they really died, Unknowing why they're there. Our finest men, our fighting folk Built of our finest of stock. Some would die by knife and gun, Some with their back to a block The sea, the land, the sky itself. Each became death over life, So did end the lives of men, Which did so in struggle and strife. No peace for them, no long goodbye's, No notes or final say. A moments thought for all they loved, Before they fade away. Some still lay where they fell, Some graves are only a name An empty space in an empty row And each of them all look the same. Some may say, as together they lay, This is what they would choose. As brothers they rest among our best, With nothing at all left to loose. But I protest, I mourn their death, As a crime on each soul and the truth. They're far more, than a hole in the floor, Had they been old or in youth. The cenotaph sits so big and so proud, So far from the death and the cost. It shows not the faces of each of the slain, Nor the families to whom they were lost. Plaques, memorials, photo's and film. They each claim to speak for the dead, How many I wonder would have died for a lie, If it was truth that was upheld instead. Still they sit in their military pit, Some have done so for years, Each demise, forever closed eyes. Leaving much heartache and tears Pass now their graves and give them a glimpse, Read all the names that you can, There will be listed the year they were robbed, And the year in which they began. Give them a thought so somebody will, Ponder as to how they departed. Their life meant more than the reasons of war, With some over before they had started. The young they tore them self to shreds, In fear of their lives till the last They cried and stabbed and shot and fell, They died be it slow or it fast. They died all the same, no matter how kind No matter how brave or meek. From children to men, without knowing when, Lost all that made them unique. Those who tell the stories of war Do so in disguise and distain Lives are not a political tool, Nor are they financial gain. We'll never hear from those who've gone, Their voices are trapped in the past. If we could go back we'd change all that was, We'd stop every shot and blast. New rows stack upon themselves Though these stacks they never seem dirty. They list the age of so many lost, With so many under thirty. The teenagers rest beside the men, The young men rest there as well. I wonder what was on their mind, As they faced that murderous hell. Lieutenants, pilots, gunners and sergeants, Guard now the ground where they lay The sailor's, Parras, colonels and privates Act now as public display. From far and wide each was found, They meet for the first time in death. They felt so proud and duty bound, Until their very last breath. Lies have reigned for far too long, Affecting the minds of the pure, It‚Äôs illness plagues all of mankind, And often has no cure. There‚Äôs many who died with God on their side, Or so at least they thought, They instead met demise in utter surprise No matter how hard they fought. They're scattered across our nations, In graveyards far and wide, Even if you found each one, It‚Äôs a fraction of who died. No eye could see, the space they‚Äôd cover. For tens of miles they‚Äôd row The horizon itself would be blocked out By the numbers no-one would know. The unknown soldier rests beneath, His tiny cross-like stake His story‚Äôs gone and will never be told, Without even so much as a wake.
